1
00:00:18,000 --> 00:00:23,000
Family Plot

2
00:00:39,700 --> 00:00:43,810
Someone is here.

3
00:00:43,810 --> 00:00:47,510
Not closely.

4
00:00:47,510 --> 00:00:51,480
Not willingly.

5
00:00:51,480 --> 00:00:55,220
I feel a holding back.

6
00:00:55,220 --> 00:00:58,690
What's the trouble, Henry?

7
00:00:59,620 --> 00:01:04,760
Too many memories, too much pain.

8
00:01:04,760 --> 00:01:09,250
Too... much... sorrow.

9
00:01:12,900 --> 00:01:15,870
Whoever is there with you,

10
00:01:15,870 --> 00:01:19,640
tell them to speak up, Henry.

11
00:01:19,640 --> 00:01:22,810
Tell them to come closer.

12
00:01:22,810 --> 00:01:26,650
I think I know who it is, Madame Blanche.

13
00:01:26,650 --> 00:01:29,680
I think I know what's bothering her.

14
00:01:29,680 --> 00:01:33,520
Her, is it? Never you mind, Miss Rainbird.

15
00:01:33,520 --> 00:01:37,320
I won't have you doing Henry's work for him.

16
00:01:37,930 --> 00:01:41,960
Now, let's have it, my love. That's why we're here tonight.

17
00:01:41,960 --> 00:01:44,900
To help my friend be rid of her torment.

18
00:01:45,190 --> 00:01:47,690
She has a right to rest her weary head

19
00:01:47,690 --> 00:01:49,820
on a pillow each night...

20
00:01:49,840 --> 00:01:53,840
and sleep the peaceful sleep of the angels.

21
00:01:53,840 --> 00:01:57,080
How did you know about my troubled sleep?

22
00:01:57,470 --> 00:01:58,890
Who told you?

23
00:01:59,050 --> 00:02:01,100
Her nights cannot go on like this much longer.

24
00:02:02,620 --> 00:02:05,850
I never told a soul about my nightmares.

25
00:02:05,850 --> 00:02:09,220
- How could you...  - Who is this person who arrives...

26
00:02:09,220 --> 00:02:13,160
in our presence tonight, but does not dare to come close to us?

27
00:02:13,160 --> 00:02:18,070
It's her. It's my sister Harriet.

28
00:02:18,070 --> 00:02:22,500
- It must be.  - She stays her distance,

29
00:02:22,500 --> 00:02:25,240
Julia Rainbird, for she does not feel...

30
00:02:25,240 --> 00:02:27,480
your love or your kindness yet.

31
00:02:27,480 --> 00:02:31,780
There is selfishness where you are.

32
00:02:31,780 --> 00:02:34,750
I've had all I can take from her.

33
00:02:34,750 --> 00:02:38,150
Night after night, coming into my dreams.

34
00:02:38,150 --> 00:02:42,420
Whining, complaining, trying to make me feel guilty,

35
00:02:42,420 --> 00:02:45,630
as though I need her to tell me right from wrong.

36
00:02:45,630 --> 00:02:49,700
Tell her I know what has to be done.

37
00:02:49,700 --> 00:02:53,230
I've been wanting to do it for a year.

38
00:02:53,230 --> 00:02:58,100
But it is I, Julia Rainbird, who has made the decision.

39
00:02:58,840 --> 00:03:02,110
I don't need her to goad me on!

40
00:03:02,110 --> 00:03:07,180
They're making me ill with their ugly words in my ugly dreams.

41
00:03:07,180 --> 00:03:10,950
Tell her to stop it, to go away and leave me alone.

42
00:03:10,950 --> 00:03:14,990
Oh, no. No, no. Don't let her go!

43
00:03:14,990 --> 00:03:18,560
- Don't let her go away.  - Harriet?

44
00:03:18,560 --> 00:03:20,730
Harriet, stay with us, Harriet.

45
00:03:20,730 --> 00:03:23,710
Your sister wants to speak to you now,

46
00:03:23,740 --> 00:03:25,910
from the depths of her soul.

47
00:03:28,170 --> 00:03:30,570
What's wrong? What is it?

48
00:03:30,570 --> 00:03:34,680
She says, "I've waited so long...

49
00:03:34,680 --> 00:03:36,810
"to hear from you, Julia.

50
00:03:36,810 --> 00:03:40,440
I've been so unhappy without you."

51
00:03:42,050 --> 00:03:44,990
It is you, Harriet.

52
00:03:44,990 --> 00:03:48,220
Oh, I'm so sorry!

53
00:03:48,220 --> 00:03:51,230
I-I should never have made you do it.

54
00:03:51,230 --> 00:03:54,230
Oh, it's all past now.

55
00:03:54,230 --> 00:03:57,670
But I'll do what I can to make up for it.

56
00:03:57,670 --> 00:04:02,000
If he's still alive, I'll find your son.

57
00:04:02,000 --> 00:04:06,040
And I'll take him in my arms and love him...

58
00:04:06,040 --> 00:04:09,040
as if I were you, my poor Harriet.

59
00:04:09,040 --> 00:04:12,780
And I'll... I'll make him one of us.

60
00:04:12,780 --> 00:04:17,120
And give him everything. Everything!

61
00:04:17,120 --> 00:04:20,190
Far away.

62
00:04:20,190 --> 00:04:22,490
So far, far away.

63
00:04:22,490 --> 00:04:26,390
Bu-But I need her. I need her help.

64
00:04:26,390 --> 00:04:29,060
I can't do it alone.

65
00:04:29,060 --> 00:04:31,100
You see, I need her memory.

66
00:04:31,100 --> 00:04:35,740
It's over 40 years ago, and I don't know where the child was taken...

67
00:04:35,740 --> 00:04:37,740
or who it was given to.

68
00:04:37,740 --> 00:04:42,310
I don't know where he is now or who he is.

69
00:04:42,310 --> 00:04:44,580
The true measure of Julia Rainbird's love...

70
00:04:44,580 --> 00:04:46,580
lies in what she does now,

71
00:04:46,580 --> 00:04:50,180
with your help, of course, and mine,

72
00:04:50,180 --> 00:04:53,320
and that of the dear, departed one...

73
00:04:53,320 --> 00:04:56,820
who has drifted so far from us.

74
00:04:56,820 --> 00:04:59,830
We understand him. Don't we, Miss Rainbird?

75
00:04:59,830 --> 00:05:05,070
Oh, yes. Yes, I do. I'm willing to do anything. Anything at all.

76
00:05:05,070 --> 00:05:08,100
In the end, there will be happiness.

77
00:05:08,100 --> 00:05:13,680
From the tears of the past, the desert of the heart will bloom.

78
00:05:13,680 --> 00:05:19,110
Good-bye, Julia Rainbird! Good-bye, Blanche.

79
00:05:22,880 --> 00:05:25,650
Good-bye.

80
00:05:26,420 --> 00:05:30,330
Madame Blanche! Are you all right?

81
00:05:30,330 --> 00:05:35,800
Oh. It was...

82
00:05:35,800 --> 00:05:37,800
What in the world's been going on here?

83
00:05:37,800 --> 00:05:40,130
I feel as though I've been properly done over.

84
00:05:40,130 --> 00:05:44,510
Don't you remember what happened? Mm-mm.

85
00:05:44,510 --> 00:05:47,740
Not the details, Miss Rainbird, only the gist, if you know what I mean.

86
00:05:47,740 --> 00:05:50,210
Suppose you give me the gist of it.

87
00:05:50,210 --> 00:05:53,580
Oh well, I wonder...

88
00:05:53,580 --> 00:05:55,920
Could I trouble you for a sip of something? Ju-Just...

89
00:05:55,920 --> 00:05:57,920
Oh, of course. What would you like?

90
00:05:57,920 --> 00:06:01,190
Oh, a double shot of anyth...

91
00:06:01,190 --> 00:06:05,350
- A spot of that sherry might be nice.  - Oh, yes. Of course.

92
00:06:09,530 --> 00:06:13,000
Thank you.

93
00:06:16,900 --> 00:06:21,780
- Now, tell me what you remember of the seance.  - In a nutshell?

94
00:06:21,780 --> 00:06:23,810
Please.

95
00:06:23,810 --> 00:06:27,120
Well...

96
00:06:27,120 --> 00:06:30,250
About 40 years ago, you arranged to have...

97
00:06:30,250 --> 00:06:33,860
your sister Harriet's baby given away without a trace.

98
00:06:33,860 --> 00:06:37,020
And now your bad dreams and troubled conscience tell you...

99
00:06:37,020 --> 00:06:39,730
to find the grown-up person, take him into the family...

100
00:06:39,730 --> 00:06:41,730
and bestow your wealth on him.

101
00:06:41,730 --> 00:06:44,400
- Excellent.  - Thank you.

102
00:06:44,400 --> 00:06:48,070
And why did I force my sister to give the child away?

103
00:06:48,070 --> 00:06:53,230
I guess the kid was a... illegitimate, Miss Rainbird.

104
00:06:54,140 --> 00:06:57,180
I don't want you to think me a puritan, Madame Blanche.

105
00:06:57,180 --> 00:07:00,980
But 40 years ago, an unmarried mother...

106
00:07:00,980 --> 00:07:03,580
was not the commonplace it is nowadays.

107
00:07:03,580 --> 00:07:05,620
And in a family like ours,

108
00:07:05,620 --> 00:07:08,560
a scandal had to be covered up at all costs.

109
00:07:08,560 --> 00:07:10,860
I understand.

110
00:07:10,860 --> 00:07:12,960
And I'm still sufficiently old-fashioned,

111
00:07:12,960 --> 00:07:15,960
and sufficiently protective of the Rainbird name,

112
00:07:15,960 --> 00:07:17,970
to want to seek the missing heir...

113
00:07:17,970 --> 00:07:21,140
in a private and secret fashion,

114
00:07:21,140 --> 00:07:24,170
rather than go to detective agencies...

115
00:07:24,170 --> 00:07:26,310
and put notices in the newspapers.

116
00:07:26,310 --> 00:07:30,470
A most wise decision, Miss Rainbird.

117
00:07:31,180 --> 00:07:35,620
Well, now, suppose we get to the reason...for my sending for you.

118
00:07:35,620 --> 00:07:38,290
I'm 78 years of age.

119
00:07:38,290 --> 00:07:41,720
I would like to go to my grave with a quiet conscience.

120
00:07:41,720 --> 00:07:46,260
Particularly as I know that my only heir is out there somewhere,

121
00:07:46,260 --> 00:07:50,300
deprived by my acts of his true Rainbird name.

122
00:07:50,300 --> 00:07:54,130
Will you help me with your powers?

123
00:07:56,540 --> 00:07:58,940
If in your heart you believe that I can,

124
00:07:58,940 --> 00:08:01,880
then I owe it to both of us to try, Miss Rainbird.

125
00:08:01,880 --> 00:08:03,950
No, I'm too old for trying.

126
00:08:03,950 --> 00:08:07,010
I've only time enough left for results!

127
00:08:07,010 --> 00:08:08,960
Find him for me, Madame Blanche.

128
00:08:08,960 --> 00:08:10,960
Use your spirit-control, your "Henry."g

129
00:08:12,620 --> 00:08:14,860
Get through to my sister.

130
00:08:14,860 --> 00:08:18,990
Find her son, whoever he is, wherever he is,

131
00:08:18,990 --> 00:08:22,500
and I'll pay you $10,000.

132
00:08:22,500 --> 00:08:26,490
Te...

133
00:08:28,540 --> 00:08:32,170
Only if you genuinely wish to, Miss Rainbird.

134
00:08:32,170 --> 00:08:36,240
But let's not think of this as a payment to me.

135
00:08:36,240 --> 00:08:38,680
There are many causes dear to my heart,

136
00:08:38,680 --> 00:08:42,150
which need all the charity the world can spare.

137
00:08:42,150 --> 00:08:45,450
You've no idea how refreshing it is for a woman of my wealth...

138
00:08:45,450 --> 00:08:48,320
to find someone who has so little use for money.

139
00:08:48,320 --> 00:08:50,420
Thank you.

140
00:08:50,420 --> 00:08:54,200
Well, now, I regard our arrangement as completed.

141
00:08:54,200 --> 00:08:58,170
I... It's my bedtime.

142
00:08:58,170 --> 00:09:00,840
I must take leave of your delightful company.

143
00:09:00,840 --> 00:09:03,870
This has been a most memorable evening for me, Miss Rainbird.

144
00:09:03,870 --> 00:09:06,840
See to it that you make it a rewarding one.

145
00:09:06,840 --> 00:09:09,510
At the risk of repeating myself,

146
00:09:09,510 --> 00:09:11,510
I hope you will not forget...

147
00:09:11,510 --> 00:09:16,020
that nobody, absolutely no one, should know of our search.

148
00:09:16,020 --> 00:09:19,290
The Rainbird name must be protected.

149
00:09:19,290 --> 00:09:21,620
My jaw is locked.

150
00:09:21,620 --> 00:09:26,250
On that note, I will say good-bye, and thank you for coming.

151
00:10:00,330 --> 00:10:02,990
So, how'd it go?

152
00:10:03,930 --> 00:10:07,270
I don't know. Having to do Henry is murder on my throat.

153
00:10:07,270 --> 00:10:11,270
- Murder.  - Yeah, yeah. I know.

154
00:10:11,270 --> 00:10:14,610
- So how did it go?  - She's hooked, waiting to be pulled in.

155
00:10:14,610 --> 00:10:17,450
Another one of your $25 sardines?

156
00:10:17,450 --> 00:10:21,580
No. This is a big one, George. A great big whale.

157
00:10:21,580 --> 00:10:23,820
Well, come on. Give.

158
00:10:23,820 --> 00:10:25,920
Keep your eyes on the road. Don't rush me.

159
00:10:25,920 --> 00:10:28,490
Okay, Blanchie.

160
00:10:28,490 --> 00:10:30,930
Start way up at the top.

161
00:10:30,930 --> 00:10:34,960
Well, it was as simple as A-B-C. Henry came to me from the Upper Brightness,

162
00:10:34,960 --> 00:10:37,500
whispered to me, "This womars been having sleep problems."

163
00:10:37,500 --> 00:10:41,170
From there on, things followed naturally, logically.

164
00:10:41,170 --> 00:10:44,470
Aha! So I came through for you again, didn't I, darlin?

165
00:10:44,470 --> 00:10:46,740
No. What are you talking about, George?

166
00:10:46,740 --> 00:10:48,940
What do you mean, what am I talking about?

167
00:10:48,940 --> 00:10:51,850
You know damn well what I'm talking about.

168
00:10:51,850 --> 00:10:54,620
All that information that I dug up by gabbir to the local druggist...

169
00:10:54,620 --> 00:10:56,620
about how she was drivir him crazy...

170
00:10:56,620 --> 00:10:58,620
tryir to get sleeping pills without a prescription!

171
00:10:58,620 --> 00:11:02,160
That could have been very, very useful to me.

172
00:11:02,160 --> 00:11:04,160
Why didn't you tell me about that?

173
00:11:04,160 --> 00:11:07,930
What do you mean, why didn't I tell you? I told you. You know damn well I told you.

174
00:11:07,930 --> 00:11:11,700
No, you always think you tell me things, and you forget to.

175
00:11:11,700 --> 00:11:15,900
I have to go through heaven and hell, the Great Beyond, with Henry.

176
00:11:15,900 --> 00:11:19,240
Henry, my ass. It was me.

177
00:11:19,240 --> 00:11:21,510
It's always me.

178
00:11:21,510 --> 00:11:24,810
Without my research, you're about as psychic as a dry salami.

179
00:11:24,810 --> 00:11:27,350
Nasty. Nasty, nasty.

180
00:11:27,350 --> 00:11:31,220
I'm sick and tired of having you hang me by the crystal balls.

181
00:11:31,220 --> 00:11:34,190
Leave your crystal balls out of this, George.

182
00:11:34,190 --> 00:11:37,790
No, let's leave Henry out of this and keep the bullshit for your customers.

183
00:11:37,790 --> 00:11:39,860
You're jealous of him, aren't you?

184
00:11:39,860 --> 00:11:42,900
Oh, please, Blanche.

185
00:11:42,900 --> 00:11:45,370
I like your jealousy. It's your driving that stinks.

186
00:11:45,370 --> 00:11:48,570
Hey, look. I happen to be an actor, not a cab driver.

187
00:11:48,570 --> 00:11:51,840
I can play cab drivers, but I sure as hell don't have to drive like one.

188
00:11:51,840 --> 00:11:54,180
Well, until I can collect from Julia Rainbird,

189
00:11:54,180 --> 00:11:56,880
I'm afraid you're gonna have to go on playing a cab driver.

190
00:11:56,880 --> 00:11:59,980
Neither of us seems to be very fond of starving to death.

191
00:11:59,980 --> 00:12:03,650
Well, how are we supposed to collect? How much is this Rainbird whale gonna spout up?

192
00:12:03,650 --> 00:12:06,820
Also, you're gonna have to go on playing a private eye.

193
00:12:06,820 --> 00:12:09,320
Christ, no! I've had it playing private eyes.

194
00:12:09,320 --> 00:12:12,860
Christ, yes! Now, George.

195
00:12:12,860 --> 00:12:15,100
Stop blaspheming.

196
00:12:15,100 --> 00:12:17,620
You wanna put the curse on ten big ones?

197
00:12:18,900 --> 00:12:21,240
Now, wait a minute, Blanche.

198
00:12:21,240 --> 00:12:24,070
- Did you say ten big ones?  - Mm-hmm.

199
00:12:24,070 --> 00:12:26,070
- Ten thousand?  - Mm-hmm.

200
00:12:26,070 --> 00:12:29,600
- Dollars?  - Dollars, George!

201
00:12:30,680 --> 00:12:33,210
Now, Blanche, you got any idea...

202
00:12:33,210 --> 00:12:36,220
what you and I could do with ten grand?

203
00:12:36,220 --> 00:12:38,350
Mm-hmm. We could even get married.

204
00:12:38,350 --> 00:12:41,290
What are you always a wet blanket for?

205
00:12:41,290 --> 00:12:43,890
Oh, you flatter me so.

206
00:12:43,890 --> 00:12:45,890
Well, what's the deal? What do we have to do?

207
00:12:45,890 --> 00:12:48,260
I'll tell you about it in bed, afterwards.

208
00:12:48,260 --> 00:12:50,870
Aw, come on, Blanche. Give me a hint.

209
00:12:50,870 --> 00:12:53,700
Just a little... Fore play.

210
00:12:53,700 --> 00:12:56,700
All right. Find one man. That's all.

211
00:12:56,700 --> 00:12:59,810
Well, we've had to do worse than that. What's his name?

212
00:12:59,810 --> 00:13:04,280
Hmm. Ah... nobody knows.

213
00:13:04,280 --> 00:13:07,720
- Well, who is he?  - That's a problem. Nobody knows.

214
00:13:07,720 --> 00:13:11,490
- Where is he?  - Nobody knows.

215
00:13:11,490 --> 00:13:14,290
Well, for chrissake! You mean, nobody knows, Blanche?

216
00:13:14,290 --> 00:13:16,720
Nobody knows his name, or where he is, or who he is?

217
00:13:16,720 --> 00:13:18,860
Well, George, stop yelling.

218
00:13:18,860 --> 00:13:22,700
There's a possibility of one person who might have known.

219
00:13:22,700 --> 00:13:26,000
- Well, who's that?  - Julia Rainbird didn't mention him to me.

220
00:13:26,000 --> 00:13:28,600
Fortunately, her friend Ida Cookson did.

221
00:13:28,600 --> 00:13:31,440
- Well, who is it?  - The Rainbird family chauffeur.

222
00:13:31,440 --> 00:13:34,780
Well, now you're talkir. Now we're on our way.

223
00:13:34,780 --> 00:13:38,710
Trouble is... Well,

224
00:13:38,710 --> 00:13:40,820
he's been dead for 25 years.

225
00:13:40,820 --> 00:13:43,120
Oh, for chrissake, Blanche...

226
00:13:43,120 --> 00:13:45,650
Oh, no, no, no, no, no, don't start to fret, George,

227
00:13:45,650 --> 00:13:48,020
or our water bed will be no fun at all tonight.

228
00:13:48,020 --> 00:13:51,260
As an actor, you should know fretting will ruin a performance.

229
00:13:51,260 --> 00:13:53,930
You're not gonna have to worry about my performance tonight.

230
00:13:53,930 --> 00:13:57,160
As a matter of fact, uh, on this very evening,

231
00:13:57,160 --> 00:14:01,330
you're gonna see a standing ovation.

232
00:14:46,110 --> 00:14:49,720
She's here. No, not a man. It's a woman.

233
00:14:49,720 --> 00:14:53,240
Right. Follow me.

234
00:15:13,210 --> 00:15:16,110
As long as you've got Victor Constantine, we can't touch you.

235
00:15:16,110 --> 00:15:19,810
So you might as well put that thing away.

236
00:15:37,260 --> 00:15:41,030
You've been calling yourself"The Trader," so we thought you were a man.

237
00:15:48,780 --> 00:15:52,210
I think we deserve some assurance that the victim is still alive.

238
00:15:57,220 --> 00:16:02,090
All radios have been removed from the helicopter, as you instructed.

239
00:16:08,960 --> 00:16:16,790
"Mr. Constantine will be unconscious but in perfect condition when picked up. Just let him sleep the drug off."

240
00:16:18,570 --> 00:16:21,010
All right, Sergeant, turn on the lights.

241
00:16:49,770 --> 00:16:52,530
- Don't try and be a hero.  - Yes, sir.

242
00:16:55,780 --> 00:16:58,210
Well, we've done our part.

243
00:17:01,250 --> 00:17:04,110
Where are we going?

244
00:17:27,210 --> 00:17:30,110
Not one goddamn mistake.

245
00:17:37,350 --> 00:17:40,650
How far are we going?

246
00:17:41,660 --> 00:17:44,020
It's lucky for you they've still got the victim.

247
00:17:44,020 --> 00:17:48,190
I'd like nothing better than to toss you right out of this thing on your head.

248
00:17:53,070 --> 00:17:56,040
You sure have this little trip mapped out, don't you?

249
00:18:00,410 --> 00:18:03,310
I bet that thing isn't even loaded.

